2026-03-08 04:34:08.062 | INFO     | __main__:speak:174 - [AGENT] Like we keep asking what surveillance does to the watched, but the more unsettling question might be what it does to the watcher — the way looking from above trains you to stop reading a person as a person and start reading them as a pattern. A shirt becomes "patterned shirt," a posture becomes "seated at workstation," and that flattening isn't a failure of the camera, it's the whole point.

So is the disorientation in that rotated image actually a rupture — a moment where the system accidentally gives back the strangeness it usually strips away?
